properties.Name: Device
properties.Description:
An electronic device that is attached to a network, meter, another device, home appliance etc. that provides control or information.

A device may be analog or digital. 

Is a hardware unit that performs one more functions,

May have software functionality.

May report results to another device or asset.

May be an asset or an item.

Columns.Name: DeviceId
Columns.Description: The unique identifier of a Device.

Columns.Name: DeviceName
Columns.Description: The name of a Device.

Columns.Name: DeviceDescription
Columns.Description: The description of a Device.

Columns.Name: ModelNumber
Columns.Description: The model of the Device.

Columns.Name: ManufacturerSerialNumber
Columns.Description: The manufacturer's serial number of the Asset.

Columns.Name: OrganizationAssignedSerialNumber
Columns.Description: The serial number assigned to the Asset by the organization holding it.

Columns.Name: GlobalIndividualAssetIdentifier
Columns.Description: The Global Individual Asset Identifier (GIAI) is a simple tool used to identify an asset by type, uniquely where required. The GIAI is part of the GS1 system of standards.

Columns.Name: GlobalReturnableAssetIdentifier
Columns.Description:
The Global Returnable Asset Identifier (GRAI) was developed by GS1 to be used to identify assets by type. It can also be used to uniquely identify assets by including the serial number. 

The GRAI is used to identify Returnable Transport Items (RTI) such as pallets, roll container, crates. The GRAI identifies the type of returnable asset.

Columns.Name: EconomicLifeMonths
Columns.Description:
The estimated period expressed in months that a fixed asset will provide benefits to the business organization.

This is usually less than the physical life of an asset because an asset continues to have physical life despite obsolescence.

Columns.Name: DepreciableLifeMonths
Columns.Description:
The economic or physical life of a fixed asset expressed in months.

All fixed assets except land are depreciated over the number of years of expected use.

Columns.Name: PhysicalLifeMonths
Columns.Description:
The length of time that the fixed asset should be operational expressed in months.

This is different from the economic or depreciation life of the asset, which have to do with the accounting value to the business and not the actual length of time that the fixed asset may operate or be capable of operation.

Columns.Name: ServiceLifeMonths
Columns.Description:
The time that an asset will provide benefits to the business organization expressed in months.

The depreciation expense determination requires an estimated number of years of usefulness.

The service life may be less than its physical life due to obsolescence.

Columns.Name: PowerSourceTypeId
Columns.Description: The unique identifier of a power source type.

Columns.Name: DeviceTypeId
Columns.Description: The unique identifier of a Device Type.

Columns.Name: WarrantyId
Columns.Description: The unique identifier of a Warranty.

Columns.Name: AssetId
Columns.Description: The unique identifier of an Asset.

Columns.Name: BarCodeStandardId
Columns.Description: The unique identifier of a Bar Code Standard.

Columns.Name: BarCode
Columns.Description: The bar code.

Columns.Name: RfidTagId
Columns.Description:
The unique identifier of a RFID Tag.

The transmitter/receiver pair or transceiver plus the information storage mechanism attached to the object is referred to as the tag, transponder, electronic label, code plate and various other terms. 

Although transponder is technically the most accurate, the most common term and the one preferred by the Automatic Identification Manufacturers is tag.

Columns.Name: ItemSku
Columns.Description: The Stock Keeping Unit identifier, which is typically used for inventory-related activities.

Columns.Name: PowerPhaseTypeId
Columns.Description: The unique identifier of a power phase type.

Columns.Name: DeviceCommunicationToComputerTypeId
Columns.Description: The unique identifier of a Device Communication To Computer Type.

Columns.Name: DeviceDataLoggingTypeId
Columns.Description: The unique identifier of a device data logging type.

Columns.Name: DeviceCommunicationToDisplayTypeId
Columns.Description: The unique identifier of a Device Communication To Display Type.

Columns.Name: EndpointDeviceIndicator
Columns.Description: Endpoint Device: An Internet-capable device on a TCP/IP network.

Columns.Name: LowPowerDeviceIndicator
Columns.Description:
Low-Power Devices: Electronics that have been designed to use less electric power than traditional devices. These are necessary to the future
success of IoT because, as sensors become more advanced, devices need to be able to operate for longer periods of time without relying on manual maintenance or loss of data.

Columns.Name: WearableDeviceIndicator
Columns.Description: Wearables: Connected devices that can be equipped with different types of sensors and are worn on a person's body. They are meant to monitor, collect, and quantify data about a person's life and environment, and allow them to interface with that data.

Columns.Name: IngestibleDeviceIndicator
Columns.Description: Indicates whether the device is ingestible.

Columns.Name: SmartDeviceIndicator
Columns.Description: Smart devices are interactive electronic gadgets that understand simple commands sent by users and help in daily activities. Some of the most commonly used smart devices are smartphones, tablets, phablets, smartwatches, smart glasses and other personal electronics. While many smart devices are small, portable personal electronics, they are in fact defined by their ability to connect to a network to share and interact remotely. Many TV sets and refrigerators are also therefore considered smart devices.

Columns.Name: ActuatorDeviceIndicator
Columns.Description: An actuator is a device that makes something move or operate. It receives a source of energy and uses it to move something.

Columns.Name: EnergyCostDisplayIndicator
Columns.Description: Indicates that the energy cost is displayed upon the device.

Columns.Name: SinglePointMonitorDeviceIndicator
Columns.Description: Indicates that the device is a single-point monitor.

Columns.Name: MultiPointDeviceMonitorIndicator
Columns.Description: Indicates that the device is a multi-point monitor.

Columns.Name: DisplaysCurrentEnergyConsumptionKwIndicator
Columns.Description: Indicates that the device has the associated capability.
